  "prompt": "The bond angle of Sulphur dioxide is greater than that of Ozone. Why?",
  "response": "The bond angle in sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082) is greater than that in ozone (O\u2083) primarily due to the differences in molecular geometry and the presence of lone pairs of electrons.\n\n1. **Molecular Geometry**:\n   - **Sulfur Dioxide (SO\u2082)**: The molecular geometry of SO\u2082 is bent (or V-shaped) due to the presence of one lone pair of electrons on the sulfur atom. The bond angle in SO\u2082 is approximately 120 degrees. The presence of the lone pair causes some repulsion, but the overall structure allows for a relatively larger bond angle compared to ozone.\n   - **Ozone (O\u2083)**: The geometry of ozone is also bent, but it has a smaller bond angle of about 117 degrees. This is because ozone has a resonance structure that includes a double bond between one of the oxygen atoms and the central oxygen atom, which introduces more electron density in that region. Additionally, ozone has two lone pairs of electrons on the central oxygen atom, which increases electron-electron repulsion and reduces the bond angle.\n\n2. **Lone Pair Repulsion**:\n   - In ozone, the presence of two lone pairs on the central oxygen atom contributes to greater repulsion. Lone pairs take up more space than bonding pairs, which can compress the bond angles between the bonded atoms. In contrast, sulfur dioxide only has one lone pair, allowing for a slightly larger bond angle.\n\nIn summary, the bond angle in sulfur dioxide is greater than that in ozone due to differences in molecular geometry, the number of lone pairs, and the resulting electron repulsion effects.",
